    <item>
      <title>Neutrality in Fiction</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/docs/books/gilmore-apt-imagining/neutrality-in-fiction/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 10 Jun 2024 18:19:53 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/docs/books/gilmore-apt-imagining/neutrality-in-fiction/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;John Gilmore defines the continuity view about expressive emotions, as emotions that are apt &lt;em&gt;if and only if&lt;/em&gt; they correctly represent the source of that emotion, if that source has the qualities that are relevant for the expression of that emotion.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The envy I feel in thinking that my colleague cruises around town on a vintage Vespa &lt;em&gt;motorino&lt;/em&gt; is inapt if he does no such thing.&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:1&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;However, there is reason to think that the criteria which an emotion&amp;rsquo;s apt expressions are grounded in are dependent on question of whether the source is real of fictional. What grounds the criterial qualities of emotionally apt responses to fiction are the functions that prompt the source.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
